he extreme weather placed upon it CPT </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">participated in and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ded evidence to the DfT report led by David Quarmby and also the report conducted by the Local Government Association. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">showed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that where the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Highways Agency and local authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ighways departments had worked in partnership to plan a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coordinated response to decide what level of bus services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> could </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and concentrated on delivering that plan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> bus services in those </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">better than where they had been no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coordination and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rather </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">haphazard response by local authorities and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their road gritting teams. There is now an acknowledgement that roads around bus depots need to be part of the priority gritting routes if bus services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are to be maintained </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">even when the depots are located in industrial estates and away from main roads.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CPT </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> asked a number of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> members across the country whether there has been any improvement in communications between the local authorities and the bus companies to draw up winter resilience plans to decide how both parties will react </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">snow and ice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">develop </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on the local bus network. The responses have been mixed across the country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Northumbria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Arriva now meet more regularly to decide what bus routes they will try to keep operational in a priority order</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> whereas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Derby</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Derbyshire </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bus routes have dropped off the priority roads list</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The position in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Bristol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has improved dramatically</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Bristol City Council and First have agreed on the main roads and bus routes the council will treat as priority routes for gritting and t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his plan is scheduled for review each October. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The bus companies have also made a number of changes with many now geared up to getting the latest information out to customers through their websites, social media, local radio etc.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is general concer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n that this winter, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">due to budgetary constraints</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uthorities may not be able to provide the level of gritting services they have in previous years and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this may impair </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the ability of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bus compan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to provide the same levels of services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The posi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of course</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will not be known </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unless and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">until extreme weather arrives this winter. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CPT expects that at the very least the dialogue on winter resilience plans will continue between local authorities and the bus companies even if only a very </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">limited response is available by the local authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style